Jessie hails from Massachusetts, and this will be her first year teaching after several years‚Äô experience through substituting, paraprofessional positions, and coordinating an after-school program. What she loves most about working with kids is being a role model and inspire them to be excited and motivated about their learning. Her goal is to have her students leave the classroom feeling confident in all their abilities, not only academically but outside of the classroom as well!

Jessie enjoys spending time with friends and family and caring for her dog Cooper and cat Sadie. She loves reading (huge Stephen King fan), traveling, yoga, and tending to her growing house plant collection! Welcome to Fuller School, Jessie!

All schools shall implement frequent hand washing procedures that align with the CDC Guidance Considerations for Schools. While hand sanitizer has become an acceptable and convenient way to clean hands, the best method for maintaining hand hygiene is with soap and water. Here are the five steps to washing your hands the right way as recommended in the "CDC When and How to Wash Your Hands" guidelines:

1. Wet your hands with clean, running water (warm or cold), turn off the tap, and apply soap.
2. Lather your hands by rubbing them together with the soap. Lather the backs of your hands, between your fingers, and under your nails.
3. Scrub your hands for at least 20 seconds. Need a timer? Hum the ‚ÄúHappy Birthday‚Äù song from beginning to end twice.
4. Rinse your hands well under clean, running water.
5. Dry your hands using a clean towel or air dry them.

Hand hygiene will begin as soon as anyone enters the buildings. A hand sanitizing station shall be located at the entrance and upon arrival, all students, staff and essential visitors shall sanitize their hands.

¬°Hola! (Don't worry about trying to say my last name. You can call me Mr. B. -- or Profe B. in Spanish.)
The proud hiking companion of two dare-devil rabbits, I'm coming to KMS in my sixth year of teaching Middle School Spanish. I am actually coming back to the area: I used to work down the road in Hancock, teaching outdoor skills at a magical place called Sargent Camp, many moons ago. In recent years, however, I have taken on the rewarding work of teaching Spanish in the classroom. I am so glad to be back in the Monadnock Region!

The thing I love most about teaching Spanish is helping learners express themselves and their ideas in a new language, as they discover for themselves the best-kept secret of language-learning: It's easier than you think! After all, our brains are hard-wired for language!

When I'm not teaching, you can find me in one of three places: curled up with a good book, out among the trees and mountains of New Hampshire, or on a paddleboard crewed by Captain Hatchet (the gray one) and First Mate Auger (the white one).

In a July 14th Press Release, CDC Director Dr. Robert Redfield is quoted as saying, ‚ÄúCloth face coverings are one of the most powerful weapons we have to slow and stop the spread of the virus ‚Äì particularly when used universally within a community setting. All Americans have a responsibility to protect themselves, their families and their communities.‚Äù

ALL students and staff members shall wear a face covering while at school, unless a medically documented accommodation is required. Each district will make a reusable, washable face covering available for every student and staff member upon request.

Anyone arriving at a school (students, staff, and essential visitors) without a covering will be provided a disposable face covering prior to entry into the building.

The screening solution we are implementing for our school buildings will include a series of prompts consistent with the current CDC Screening Guidelines as of July 31, 2020 (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/symptom-screening.html).

The prompts will ask people to respond to:
- Temperature of 100.4 or higher
- Sore throat
- New uncontrolled cough that causes difficulty breathing
- Shortness of breath
- Diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, or abdominal pain
- Fatigue, body aches, headache
- Loss of taste or smell

- Any travel to/from areas outside of New England (VT, ME, MA, CT, RI) within the last 14 days (starting from the last day of their travel outside New England), irrespective of the mode of transportation for travel.

Artwork by Thomas Nowill.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

Artwork by Reagan Hopkins.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

After 14 years at Keene High School, having served the last six as principal, Jim Logan is stepping down at the end of this academic year.

Jim says that what he has enjoyed "hands down" most during his time here were his daily interactions with the students, walking the halls, seeing student shows and watching them playing on the athletic fields. He often dropped in on classes of all kinds to see how everyone was doing, and he will be sorely missed by many. Jim, we wish you all the best with your future endeavors, and please come visit often! (Photo by Keene Sentinel)

Artwork by Zoe Rutledge.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

This award program is sponsored by the Cheshire Children's Museum and Impact Monadnock/The Monadnock United Way.

"Jennifer was selected in part because of her ability to meet the needs of individual children, to demonstrate theory versus reality, and her communication expertise with children, families and her colleagues,‚Äù explains Deb Ganley from the Cheshire Children's Museum. ‚ÄúWe had so many excellent candidates. It was not an easy decision. Jennifer also has the responsibility of teaching future early childhood educators, so her example as a role model is critical in what she does.‚Äù

Congratulations on your achievements, Emily!

In Pueblo lore, storytellers represent the power of story and tradition. 5th graders at Symonds School studied the work or Helen Cordero, a Cochiti Pueblo pottery artist, who was famous for her storyteller pottery figurines. The children then each chose an animal and created their own clay storyteller.
